issues.body:
**Simple scenario**:
A bank manager asks an AI assistant to approve a loan. The AI asks a credit-check tool to verify the applicant credit risk analysis and similarly delegates one more task to another agent to get the credit score for verification. The spawned credit-agent needs to know: did a real bank manager ultimately authorize this, or did some random agent trigger it on its own to spawn another agent to fetch credit score.?

When Agent A delegates a task to Agent B, that delegation is an act of authority transfer — not just a function call. actchain describes who is calling. delegation_chain term describes who authorized whom to call whom.

**Why delegation_chain, not actchain**
1.  actchain also carries the same meaning, but somewhere not resonating with delegation as core concept.
2. delegation_chain is a specific term describes who authorized whom to call whom.
3. delegation_depth as a companion integer allows any service to enforce max-hop policies without traversing the nested chain.

**Proposed claim**
"delegation_chain": {
  "act": {
    "sub": "credit-check-tool",
    "act": {
      "sub": "ai-assistant",
      "act": {
        "sub": "bank-manager@bank.com"
      }
    }
  }
}
"delegation_depth": 3

